Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: 4:07 Defendant Maria Evelyn Ingersoll in court with attorney Phillip Helgeson.  William H. Thorie appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Defendant Maria Evelyn Ingersoll in custody.  15CM194 and 15CM233 heard at this time. Thorie: 15CM102 recommendation for 45 days jail with credit for time for a release date of December 26, 2015. 15CM233 guilty to Ct#1, dismiss Ct#2. 15CM194 dismiss. 24 days jail on 15CM233 with credit to allow release on December 26, 2015. Helgeson agrees but free to argue less jail time.   Plea Questionnaire and Waiver of Rights form is filed with the court; court reviews with Def.  Constitutional rights explained to defendant.  Exam'd re: understanding of law, penalty and rights. Def pleas guilty to Ct#1 in 15CM233; Helgeson stipulates to a factual basis.  COURT ACCEPTS PLEA, FINDS DEF FREELY, INTELLIGENTLY, KNOWINGLY & UNDERSTANDINGLY MADE AND WAIVES CONSTITUTIONAL RIGHTS. Court finds and adjudicates Def guilty to Ct#1 in 15CM233. Dismisses Ct#2 in 15CM233 and 15CM194. Thorie addresses sentencing. Helgeson addresses sentencing; asks for 40 days on 15CM102 and 20 on 15CM233 to allow release before Christmas. (in custody since November 23, 2015) Court orders: 15CM102 45 days jail with credit to allow release date of December 26, 2015. Orders 24 days jail with credit to allow release date of December 26, 2015 on 15CM233; concurrent to 15CM102.  Appeal rights are given to the defendant.
filed by Probation Agent Tricia Gilby
